{"title_page": "Devin Haney", "text_new": "{{short description|American boxer}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n|name        = Devin Haney\n|image       = Devin Haney 2019 picture.jpg\n|caption     = Haney in 2019\n|realname    = \n|nickname    = The Dream<ref name=BoxRec>{{cite web|title=Devin Haney|url=http://boxrec.com/en/boxer/741718|website=BoxRec|accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref>\n|weight      = {{plainlist|\n*[[Lightweight]]\n}}\n|height      = 5 ft 8 inches<ref name=BoxRec />\n|reach       = 71 inches<ref name=BoxRec />\n|nationality = American\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1998|11|17|}}\n|birth_place = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.<ref name=BoxRec />\n|style       = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]<ref name=BoxRec />\n|total       = 24\n|wins        = 24\n|KO          = 15\n|losses      = 0\n|draws       = \n|no contests = \n}}\n\n'''Devin Haney''' (born November 17, 1998) is an American [[professional boxer]] who has held the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[lightweight]] title since 2019. As of November 2019, Haney is ranked as the world's third-best active [[lightweight]] by ''[[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]]'' magazine<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ringtv.com/ratings/?weightclass=281 |title=Lightweight ratings |date=2019-08-20 |website=The Ring |access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref>, fifth by the [[Transnational Boxing Rankings Board]] and sixth by [[BoxRec]].\n\nIn 2019, Haney became the youngest world champion in 23 years after being promoted from WBC [[Interim champion|interim]] to full champion status.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/devin-haney-im-ready-return-im-coming-all-belts--145099|title=Devin Haney: When I'm Ready To Return, I'm Coming For All Belts!|last=|first=|date=13 December 2019|website=BoxingScene.com|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Amateur career==\nAs an amateur, Haney won seven National titles. In January 2015, aged 17, he became the youngest boxer to win the [[Youth World Boxing Championships|Youth World Championships]] in [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]]. He had an amateur record of 138\u20138 bouts before turning professional in 2015 at the age of 17.\n\nUSA Junior National Championships Silver medalist in Mobile\n'''2013'''\n*Defeated [[Nikita Ababiy]] 3:0\n*Defeated Duke Ragen 3:0\n*Defeated Michael Dutchover 2:1\n*Lost to Ruben Villa 1:2\n\nWorld Junior Championships quarter-finalist in Kiev, Ukraine'''2013''\n*Defeated Elmaddin Ismailov (Azerbaijan) 2:1\n*Defeated Sabyrzhan Abilov (Kazakhstan) 2:1\n*Lost to Suleyman Bammatov (Russia) 0:3\n\nUS Junior National Championships Gold medalist in Reno '''2014'''\n*Defeated Adolfo Alanis 3:0\n*Defeated Alejandro Campa 3:0\n*Defeated [[Ryan Garcia]] 3:0\n\nUSA Youth National Championships Gold medalist in Reno '''2015'''\n*Defeated Daiyaan Butt 3:0\n*Defeated Alejandro Guerrero 3:0\n*Defeated [[Ryan Garcia]] 3:0\n*Defeated Bryan Lua 3:0\n*Defeated Andres Cortes 2:1\n\n==Professional career==\nHaney turned pro at the age of 16 but could not compete in the United States due to the minimum age regulation, so his first four fights were in Mexico. At regional level he won the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] Youth, [[IBF]]-USBA, IBF North American, WBC International, [[WBO]] Inter-Continental and [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] International [[lightweight]] titles as a professional.\n\nOn February 2, 2018 Haney was scheduled to fight Filipino Harmonito Dela Torre in an eight-round opening bout. Dela Torre had problems obtaining a visa and subsequently withdrew from the fight. Unable to find an opponent, the date was scrapped.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2018/1/29/16948490/devin-haneys-shobox-fight-canceled|title=Devin Haney\u2019s ShoBox fight canceled|website=www.badlefthook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Haney signed a co-promotional deal between his own company, Devin Haney Promotions, and British promoter [[Eddie Hearn]]'s [[Matchroom Boxing]]. In September 2019, Haney defeated Zaur Abdulaev (11-0) for the WBC [[Interim championship|interim]] lightweight title, and later became the youngest world champion in boxing when he was elevated as the [[List of WBC world champions#Lightweight|WBC lightweight champion]] after previous WBC lightweight champion [[Vasyl Lomachenko]] was promoted to \"Franchise Champion\" by the WBC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/27914825/wbc-gives-plans-titlists-names-vasiliy-lomachenko-franchise-champ|title=WBC maps out next fights, strips Lomachenko|date=2019-10-24|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> On the undercard of [[KSI vs. Logan Paul II]] in November 2019, Haney made his first title defense against [[Alfredo Santiago]] (12-0), and won by unanimous decision. He injured his shoulder during the fight, requiring surgery that would keep him out until the summer of 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/28592981/devin-haney-expects-early-summer-return-shoulder-surgery|title=Haney eyes summer bout after shoulder surgery|date=2020-01-29|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> He maintained the title \"champion in recess.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/04/19/sport/devin-haney-racist-deny-vasyl-lomachenko-spt-intl/index.html|title=Undefeated boxer denies being racist after saying he would 'never lose to a white boy'|first=Ben |last=Morse|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> \n\nHaney claimed that he could beat unified lightweight champion [[Vasyl Lomachenko]] during an interview with 78SportsTV in April 2020. When asked if would \"end the hype of Loma\", Haney said, \"I\u2019ll tell you this. I will never lose to a white boy in my life. I don\u2019t care what nobody got to say. Fight a white boy 10 times, I\u2019m going to beat him 10 times.\" Haney was criticized for this comment, with many saying it was anti-white racism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/boxing/devin-haney-racist-twitter-never-lose-to-white-boy-lomachenko-a9472781.html|title=Devin Haney criticised after claiming \u2018he would never lose to a white boy\u2019|date=2020-04-19|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Haney came out on Twitter after and said, \"I'm not racist and I never will be a racist. I'm chasing greatness.\" He also said he spoke with WBC president [[Mauricio Sulaim\u00e1n]] and \"confirmed to him directly my commitment to be a role model and my absolute rejection of discrimination of any kind.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/52341296|title=Devin Haney 'rejects discrimination' after comments about Vasyl Lomachenko fight|date=2020-04-18|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-04-19|language=en-gb}}</ref> Haney's comments were compared to [[Bernard Hopkins]]' declaration that he would \"never let a white boy beat me\" before his [[Bernard Hopkins vs. Joe Calzaghe|fight with Joe Calzaghe]], which Hopkins lost.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/52341296|title=Devin Haney 'rejects discrimination' after comments about Vasyl Lomachenko fight|date=2020-04-18|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-04-19|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHaney lived in [[Oakland, California]] as a child, but moved with his father to [[Las Vegas]]. He started boxing at the age of seven after getting into fights at school.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|draws=\n|nc=\n|ko-wins=15\n|ko-losses=\n|dec-wins=9\n|dec-losses=\n|dq-wins=\n|dq-losses=\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|24\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|24\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flagicon|DOM}} Alfredo Santiago\n|UD\n|12\n|[[KSI vs. Logan Paul 2|Nov 9, 2019]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Staples Center]], [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Retained [[List of WBC world champions#Lightweight|WBC lightweight title]]}}\n|-\n|23\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|23\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flagicon|RUS}} Zaur Abdullaev\n|RTD\n|4 (12), {{small|3:00}}\n|Sep 13, 2019\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Hulu Theater]], [[New York City, New York]], U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Won vacant [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[Interim championship|interim]] lightweight title}}\n|-\n|22\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|22\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flagicon|MEX}} Antonio Moran\n|KO\n|7 (12), {{small|2:32}}\n|May 25, 2019\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[MGM National Harbor]], [[Oxon Hill, Maryland]], U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Retained WBC International and WBO Inter-Continental lightweight titles;<br>Won vacant [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] International lightweight title}} \n|-\n|21\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|21\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flagicon|RSA}} Xolisani Ndongeni\n|UD\n|10\n|Jan 11, 2019\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flagicon|USA}} {{small|StageWorks, [[Shreveport, Louisiana]], U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Won vacant WBC International and [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] Inter-Continental titles}}\n|-\n|20\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|20\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Juan Carlos Burgos]]\n|UD\n|10\n|Sep 28, 2018\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Pechanga Resort & Casino]], [[Temecula, California]], U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Won vacant [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] North American lightweight title}}\n|-\n|19\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|19\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flagicon|USA}} Mason Menard \n|RTD\n|9 (10), {{small|3:00}}\n|May 11, 2018\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flagicon|USA}} {{small|2300 Arena, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, U.S.}}   \n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{smal