jab\n|Deep Jandu, DIVINE\n|Deep Jandu\n|}\n\n=== Promotional Tracks ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Song\n!Artist(s)\n!Producer(s)\n!For\n|-\n\n|2017\n|Shuffle\n|Divine, Siri Narayan\n|Sid Vashi\n|[[Bacardi]] Breezer Vivid\n|-\n|2017\n|Suede Gully\n|Mukti Mohan, Divine, Khasi Bloodz, Prabh Deep, Madurai Souljours\n|Sneha Khanwalkar\n|[[Puma (brand)|PUMA]]\n|-\n|2018\n|Kaam 25\n|Divine\n|Adarsh shrivastav\n|[[Sacred Games (TV series)]]\n|-\n|2019\n|NY Se Mumbai\n|Nas, Divine, Naezy, Ranveer Singh\n|XD Pro, iLL Wayno\n|[[Gully Boy]]\n|-\n|2019\n|Be a King\n|Divine, Siri Narayan\n|\n|[[Budweiser]] Experiences\n|-\n|2019\n|Chakravyuh mein #SockThem\n|Divine\n|Karan Kanchan, Divine\n|[[Puma (brand)|PUMA]]\n|-\n|2019\n|Legends\n|Divine, Aditi Ramesh\n|Karan Kanchan\n|[[Red Bull BC One]]\n|}\n\n=== Playback Singer ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Film\n!Song\n!Singer(s)\n!Producer(s)\n|-\n|2017\n|[[Rum (film)|Rum]]\n|Pori Pathi Vizhum\n|Diwakar, Divine \n|Vijaya Raghavendra\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2018\n|''[[Mukkabaaz]]''\n|Paintra\n|Divine\n|[[Nucleya]]\n|-\n|[[Blackmail (2018 film)|Blackmail]]\n|Badla\n|[[Amit Trivedi]], Divine\n|Kiran Das\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |2019\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Gully Boy]]\n|Apna Time Aayega (as lyricist)\n|[[Ranveer Singh]]\n|Dub Sharma, Divine\n|-\n|Azadi\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Divine\n|Dub Sharma, Divine\n|-\n|Sher Aya Sher\n|Chandrashekar Kunder\n|-\n|Mere Gully Mein \n|Ranveer Singh, Divine, [[Naezy]]\n|Sez On The Beat\n|-\n|Doori (as lyricist)\n|Ranveer Singh\n|[[Rishi Rich]]\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Song !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| 2013 || Rolling Stone India 2013 || Best Video Award || Yeh Mera Bombay || {{won}} ||\n|-\n| 2018 || Outlook Social Media Award || Musician of the Year || {{n/a}} || {{won}} || \n|-\n| 2015 || [[Global Indian Music Academy Awards|GIMA Awards]] || Best EDM Track of the Year || Jungle Raja ('''Bass Rani''') by Nucleya || {{won}} || \n|-\n| 2020 || [[65th Filmfare Awards]] || [[Filmfare Award for Best Lyricist|Best Lyrics]] || '''Apna Time Aayega''' ([[Gully Boy]]) with Ankur Tiwari || {{won}} || <ref>{{cite news |title=Kesari lyricist Manoj Muntashir vows to boycott award shows as Filmfare Best Lyrics award goes to Gully Boy |url=https://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/news/kesari-lyricist-manoj-muntashir-vows-boycott-award-shows-filmfare-best-lyrics-award-goes-gully-boy-508291 |accessdate=19 February 2020 |work=PINKVILLA |language=en}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Documentaries ==\n\n* ''Gully Life: Story of Divine.'' 2019 documentary, [[Discovery Channel (India)|Discovery Channel]], 50 min.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/tv/gully-life-review-discovery-s-documentary-takes-a-shallow-dive-into-divine-s-life/story-elMcA3Ejes6i4fPoOqLJyL.html |title=Gully Life review: Discovery\u2019s documentary takes a shallow dive into Divine\u2019s life |date=2019-07-01 |website=Hindustan Times |language=en |access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Twitter|VivianDivine|name=DIVINE}}\n* {{Instagram|vivianakadivine|name=DIVINE}}\n[[Category:Indian rappers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image            = File:Vivian-Fernandes-Divine.webp\n| caption          = Vivian Fernandes pictured in 2018\n| Name             = DIVINE\n| background       = solo_singer<!-- this is a required field, do not change or remove -->\n| birth_name       = Vivian Fernandes\n| birth_date       = 2 October 1990\n| birth_place      = [[Andheri]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| Genre            = [[Hip Hop]], [[Rap]]\n| Occupation       = [[Rapper]], [[Lyricist]], [[Actor]]\n| Label            = [[Universal Music India]], [[Mass Appeal Records]] India, Gully Gang Entertainment, [[Red Bull]], [[Puma (brand)|Puma]], [[Netflix]], [[Sony Music India]]\n| years_active     = 2010-present\n| associated_acts  = [[Naezy]], [[Nucleya]], Rohan Thapa, [[Gangis Khan]], Deep Jandu, [[Raja Kumari]], Dub Sharma, Phenom, Sez, Karan Kanchan\n| origin           = [[Mumbai]], [[India]]\n}}\n\n'''Vivian Fernandes''', better known by his stage name '''DIVINE''', is an [[Indian people|Indian]] [[rapper]] from [[Mumbai, Maharashtra]], [[India]]. He started to gain popularity after the release of his song ''Yeh Mera Bombay.'' He broke through with the release of his song ''Mere Gully Mein'' featuring fellow Mumbai rapper [[Naezy]].\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Early years ===\nDivine started his career as an underground rapper in 2011 after discovering Hip Hop on a T-shirt. A friend of his wore a shirt of [[50 Cent]]'s first album [[Get Rich or Die Tryin'|Get Rich Or Die Tryin']] at school. The same friend would give him his first MP3 CD with hip hop music on it which inspired him to start rapping in English.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/ht-brunch-cover-story-what-makes-gully-boy-divine-the-coolest-voice-of-contemporary-indian-hip-hop/story-GRCBw3nO7eFIasAd2agzGM.html|title=HT Brunch cover story: What makes \u2018gully boy\u2019 Divine the coolest voice of contemporary Indian hip-hop|date=2019-07-06|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> He was part of the hip hop crew called ''Mumbai's Finest''. He often raps about his own life experiences, such as the life of the poor people in Mumbai and his upbringing with a single mother. He cites American rappers such as [[Nas]], [[Eminem]], [[Big L]], Gangis Khan and [[Rakim]] as his main inspirations.\n\n=== Rise to success ===\nFollowing the release of his song ''[[Yeh Mera Bombay]]'', Divine obtained the attention of [[Sony Music India]] <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://qz.com/india/1166165/hard-kaur-divine-prabh-deep-sofia-ashraf-the-year-when-indian-hip-hop-cemented-its-place-on-the-music-charts/ |title=2017: The year when Indian hip-hop cemented its place on the music charts |last=Karkare |first=Aakash |website=Quartz India |language=en |access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref> while performing at the Blue Frog Festival 2014 in Mumbai and shortly after signed a contract with them. The song later went on to win the ''Best Video of the Year'' award by Rolling Stone India in the same year. He released his breakout single ''Mere Gully Main'' featuring [[Naezy]] on 16 April 2015. The song went viral and many [[Bollywood]] celebrities shared it on social media.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Will Mumbai rapper Divine become JB Nagar's Slumdog Millionaire? |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/will-mumbai-rapper-divine-become-jb-nagars-slumdog-millionaire/17056190 |journal=Mid Day |accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>  He collaborated with Indian DJ [[Nucleya]] on Nucleya's album ''Bass Rani'', which helped him gain even more popularity. The song won ''Best EDM track of the Year'' in the GIMA Awards in 2015.\n\nOn 24 March 2016, his debut solo single ''Jungli Sher'' released and it ruled the charts because of its raw depiction of the life of the poor in Mumbai. He took the song to the Breakfast Show ahead of BBC Asian Network Live on 29 April 2016. He appeared on the [[BBC Asian Network]] in the Charlie Sloth Show and was the first Hindi-speaking rapper to freestyle on the show and also the first to rap in Hindi with the name-giving host in attendance. He was also featured on Brapp TV.<ref>{{cite journal |title=This hip-hop artist, who grew up in the slums of Mumbai, is going to London to perform on a BBC Radio show |journal=DNA India |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-this-hip-hop-artist-who-grew-up-in-the-slums-of-Mumbai-is-going-to-London-to-perform-on-a-bbc-radio-show-2199538 |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe again collaborated with Nucleya in another hit track, entitled ''Scene Kya Hai'' off Nucleya's album ''Raja Baja''. He was featured on ''Daru Daru'' with Deep Jandu and Gangis Khan, his first commercially oriented song, which came out on 10 January 2017. His next solo single ''Farak'' released on 16 February 2017 and topped the [[Indian pop|Indipop]] charts on iTunes India.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Mumbai Rapper Divine's Biographical Song Jungli Sher's Video Shot Completely On iPhones Is Taking Over The Internet |journal=IndiaTimes |url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/meet-the-mumbai-ghetto-rapper-divine-whose-biographical-rap-song-jungli-sher-s-video-shot-completely-on-iphones-is-taking-over-the-internet-252241.html |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared as a feature on a record called ''City Slums'' by Indian-American rapper/singer/songwriter [[Raja Kumari]] in May 2017. The song crossed 2 million views on YouTube within 24 hours of its release.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nIn 2018, Divine terminated his contract with Sony Music India. He released a remix to [[Lil Pump]]'s [[Gucci Gang]] called ''Gully Gang'' independently on 18 January 2018. The song was perceived well by both critics and fans and helped him garner more attention. On 5 April 2018, he followed up with ''One Side'' produced by Byg Byrd. The video was produced by [[Red Bull]] Media House and came out on the rapper's own YouTube channel.\n\nHis next single ''Teesri Manzil'' earned him a copyright strike from [[Zee Music Company]] a few hours after its release and got deleted from his channel. It was eventually re-released on 14 December 2018 with some changes in the lyrics.\n\nHe released ''Junoon'', the intro to his upcoming first full-length album on 10 November 2018. The album's name, ''Kohinoor'', was announced on 13 February 2019 on Apple Music's Beats 1 radio show hosted by [[Ebro Darden]]. The album release was announced to be somewhen in April 2019 but as of 15 April 2019 there weren't any news on the album's release.\n\nIn July 2019, Divine released a documentary film about his career so far entitled ''Gully Life - The story of DIVINE''. It first aired on TV on channels such as the Discovery Channel and was released on Divine's YouTube Channel a week later.<ref>{{Citation|title=GULLY LIFE - The Story of DIVINE (Full Movie)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hjmqRgIoHP8|language=en|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 2019, Nas' [[Mass Appeal Records]] and Universal Music India launched Mass Appeal India and signed Divine. In an interview with Nas published on Mass Appeal India's YouTube Channel <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9a-UBaeTyFY |title=The DIVINE & Nas Interview |language=en}}</ref> and Universal Music India's Facebook Page<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/universalmusicindia/videos/2399279810320101/ |title=Universal Music India - Nas and Divine's interview |language=en}}</ref> on 20 August 2019, Nas revealed that Divine's debut album ''Kohinoor'' is set to release soon. It was released on 9 October 2019 and features all-new tracks recorded specifically for the album.\n\n=== Film contributions ===\nDivine made his [[Bollywood]] debut for the film [[Mukkabaaz]] with the song ''Paintra''. The track was another collaboration with Nucleya and came out on 1 December 2017. He collaborated with famous Indian music director and singer [[Amit Trivedi]] for the [[Irrfan Khan]] Starter film [[Blackmail (2018 film)|Blackmail]] on a song ''Badla'' which came out on 16 March 2018 via [[Super Cassettes Industries T-Series|T-Series]]. He also contributed to the soundtrack for [[Sacred Games (TV series)|Sacred Games]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/tv/saif-ali-khan-to-star-in-netflix-series-sacred-games/story-AjtxogMzZezeXq5hDvWOoJ.html |title=Saif Ali Khan to star in Netflix series Sacred Games |date=14 July 2017 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=11 October 2017 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://in.bookmyshow.com/entertainment-news/tv-shows/sacred-games-first-look-intense-edge-seat-drama-awaits-viewers |title=Sacred Games First Look: An Intense Edge-Of-The-Seat Drama Awaits Viewers |website=BookMyShow |accessdate=27 February 2018}}</ref> an [[India]]n [[Netflix]] Original Series. It features his song ''Jungli Sher'' as well ''Kaam 25'' produced by Indo-Canadian producer Phenom which was made specifically for the series. Its music video was released on 14 June 2018 on both Divine's and Netflix's YouTube channels with the version on Netflix featuring English subtitles (Listen to Jungli Sher<ref>{{cite web |title=Jungli Sher - DIVINE - Official Music Video - with Lyrics & English Translation |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Wsi7YTI2nY |publisher=Youtube |accessdate=11 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and Kaam 25<ref>{{cite web |title=Kaam 25: DIVINE {{!}} Sacred Games {{!}} Netflix |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ATf05n5LBHQ |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=11 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> on YouTube).\n\nDivine most notably contributed to the soundtrack of the 2019 film [[Gully Boy]] by [[Zoya Akhtar]], a film which is inspired by the lives of Naezy and himself, with [[Ranveer Singh]] and [[Alia Bhatt]] in the lead roles. Divine and Naezy both helped as consultants to get an authentic representation of the [[Hip hop|Hip Hop culture]] for the film. Their song ''Mere Gully Mein'' was remade with Ranveer Singh rapping Naezy's lyrics as part of the film. Furthermore, Divine provided additional rap lyrics for Ranveer Singh's character and composed some of the songs for the original soundtrack. A promotional single featuring American artist [[Nas]] as well as Naezy, Divine and Ranveer Singh was released on [[JioSaavn]] shortly prior to the film's release.\n\n== Gully Gang Entertainment ==\nIn February 2019 he announced the founding of a new company, ''Gully Gang Entertainment'', a record label to recruit and produce Hip Hop talent in the Mumbai area.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/rapper-divine-announces-gully-gang-entertainment-to-record-recruit-and-produce-hip-hop-talent-2027353.html |title=Rapper Divine Announces Gully Gang Entertainment to Record, Recruit and Produce Hip Hop Talent |website=News18 |access-date=9 February 2019}}</ref> ' Gully Gang Cypher<ref>{{cite web |title=GULLY GANG CYPHER - Aavrutti, D'Evil, Shah Rule, Karan Kanchan |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Am9XxIAc0HI |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=11 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>' released on 22 May 2019, is the first song under the label and it features the emerging rap quartet Aavrutti, hip-hop artists D\u2019Evil, Shah RuLe and music producer Karan Kanchan for the project<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/its-a-wrap/article26618326.ece |title=It\u2019s a wrap for BUDX |last=Tagat |first=Anurag |date=2019-03-23 |work=The Hindu |access-date=2019-07-03 |language=en-IN |issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thewildcity.com/news/13177-divine-s-gully-gang-records-kicks-off-with-gully-gang-cypher |title=DIVINE\u2019s Gully Gang Records Kicks Off With \u2018Gully Gang Cypher\u2019 |website=www.thewildcity.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Albums ===\n\n* ''Kohinoor LP (2019)\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Song\n!Performed By\n!Written By\n!Produced By\n|-\n|Kohinoor\n|Divine\n|Divine, Benny Solomon \n|iLL Wayno\n|-\n|Wallah\n|Divine, Shah Rule\n|Divine, Phenom, Xplicit \n|Xplicit, Phenom\n|-\n|Gandhi Money\n|Divine\n|Divine, Phenom\n|Phenom\n|-\n|Nas Interlude (Skit)\n|Divine, [[Nas]]\n|Divine, [[Nas]], Phenom\n|Phenom\n|-\n|Vibe Hai\n|Divine, Aavrutti, D'Evil, Shah Rule\n|Divine, D'Evil, Frenzzy, NDS, Saifan, Sammohit, Shah Rule, Sledge \n|NDS\n|-\n|Chal Bombay\n|Divine\n|Divine, iLL Wayno, Phenom\n|Phenom, iLL Wayno\n|-\n|Remand\n|Divine, [[Dave East]]\n|Divine, [[Dave East]], Phenom\n|Phenom\n|-\n|Too Hype\n|Divine, [[Sanjoy]], [[Sid Sriram]]\n|Divine, Julian De Grosso, [[Russel Ali|Russell Ali]], [[Sanjoy]], [[Sid Sriram]], Zach Cirino\n|[[Sanjoy]] \n|}\n\n=== Singles ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Track\n!Artist(s)\n!Producer\n|-\n|2013\n|Voice Of The Streets\n|Divine\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|Yeh Mera Bombay\n| Divine\n|[[Street Academics|Rjv Ernesto]], Sez On The Beat\n|-\n|2014\n|ABE\n|Divine, Sikandar Kahlon, B Meeks\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|Mere Gully Mein\n|Divine, Naezy\n|Sez On The Beat\n|-\n|2015\n|Jungle Raja\n|Divine, Nucleya\n|Nucleya\n|-\n|2015\n|Ryder Music\n|Divine, Sikandar Kahlon\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|Jungli Sher\n|Divine\n|Sez On The Beat\n|-\n|2016\n|Mitra Da Swag\n|Divine, Sikandar Kahlon, Gangis Khan, Deep Jandu\n|Deep Jandu\n|-\n|2016\n|Farak Hai\n|Divine\n|Brapp TV\n|-\n|2016\n|Scene Kya Hai\n|Divine, Nucleya\n|Nucleya\n|-\n|2017\n|Daru Daru\n|Divine, Deep Jandu, Gangis Khan\n|Deep Jandu\n|-\n|2017\n|Farak\n|Divine\n|Phenom\n|-\n|2017\n|City Slums\n|Raja Kumari, Divine\n|Beat Busta, Jules Wolfson\n|-\n|2018\n|Gully Gang (Gucci Gang Remix)\n|Divine\n|Cyrill Gabriel (Madbus Audio)\n|-\n|2018\n|One Side\n|Divine\n|Byg Byrd\n|-\n|2018\n|Roots\n|Divine, Raja Kumari\n|K-Major\n|-\n|2018\n|Teesri Manzil\n|Divine\n|Phenom\n|-\n|2018\n|Junoon (Intro)\n|Divine\n|Phenom\n|-\n|2019\n|Age 19\n|[[Jass Manak (singer)|Jass Manak]], Divine\n|Deep Jandu\n|-\n|2019\n|Bombay To Punjab\n|Deep Jandu, DIVINE\n|Deep Jandu\n|}\n\n=== Promotional Tracks ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Song\n!Artist(s)\n!Producer(s)\n!For\n|-\n\n|2017\n|Shuffle\n|Divine, Siri Narayan\n|Sid Vashi\n|[[Bacardi]] Breezer Vivid\n|-\n|2017\n|Suede Gully\n|Mukti Mohan, Divine, Khasi Bloodz, Prabh Deep, Madurai Souljours\n|Sneha Khanwalkar\n|[[Puma (brand)|PUMA]]\n|-\n|2018\n|Kaam 25\n|Divine\n|Adarsh shrivastav\n|[[Sacred Games (TV series)]]\n|-\n|2019\n|NY Se Mumbai\n|Nas, Divine, Naezy, Ranveer Singh\n|XD Pro, iLL Wayno\n|[[Gully Boy]]\n|-\n|2019\n|Be a King\n|Divine, Siri Narayan\n|\n|[[Budweiser]] Experiences\n|-\n|2019\n|Chakravyuh mein #SockThem\n|Divine\n|Karan Kanchan, Divine\n|[[Puma (brand)|PUMA]]\n|-\n|2019\n|Legends\n|Divine, Aditi Ramesh\n|Karan Kanchan\n|[[Red Bull BC One]]\n|}\n\n=== Playback Singer ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Film\n!Song\n!Singer(s)\n!Producer(s)\n|-\n|2017\n|[[Rum (film)|Rum]]\n|Pori Pathi Vizhum\n|Diwakar, Divine \n|Vijaya Raghavendra\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2018\n|''[[Mukkabaaz]]''\n|Paintra\n|Divine\n|[[Nucleya]]\n|-\n|[[Blackmail (2018 film)|Blackmail]]\n|Badla\n|[[Amit Trivedi]], Divine\n|Kiran Das\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |2019\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Gully Boy]]\n|Apna Time Aayega (as lyricist)\n|[[Ranveer Singh]]\n|Dub Sharma, Divine\n|-\n|Azadi\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Divine\n|Dub Sharma, Divine\n|-\n|Sher Aya Sher\n|Chandrashekar Kunder\n|-\n|Mere Gully Mein \n|Ranveer Singh, Divine, [[Naezy]]\n|Sez On The Beat\n|-\n|Doori (as lyricist)\n|Ranveer Singh\n|[[Rishi Rich]]\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Song !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| 2013 || Rolling Stone India 2013 || Best Video Award || Yeh Mera Bombay || {{won}} ||\n|-\n| 2018 || Outlook Social Media Award || Musician of the Year || {{n/a}} || {{won}} || \n|-\n| 2015 || [[Global Indian Music Academy Awards|GIMA Awards]] || Best EDM Track of the Year || Jungle Raja ('''Bass Rani''') by Nucleya || {{won}} || \n|-\n| 2020 || [[65th Filmfare Awards]] || [[Filmfare Award for Best Lyricist|Best Lyrics]] || '''Apna Time Aayega''' ([[Gully Boy]]) with Ankur Tiwari || {{won}} || <ref>{{cite news |title=Kesari lyricist Manoj Muntashir vows to boycott award shows as Filmfare Best Lyrics award goes to Gully Boy |url=https://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/news/kesari-lyricist-manoj-muntashir-vows-boycott-award-shows-filmfare-best-lyrics-award-goes-gully-boy-508291 |accessdate=19 February 2020 |work=PINKVILLA |language=en}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Documentaries ==\n\n* ''Gully Life: Story of Divine.'' 2019 documentary, [[Discovery Channel (India)|Discovery Channel]], 50 min.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/tv/gully-life-review-discovery-s-documentary-takes-a-shallow-dive-into-divine-s-life/story-elMcA3Ejes6i4fPoOqLJyL.html |title=Gully Life review: Discovery\u2019s documentary takes a shallow dive into Divine\u2019s life |date=2019-07-01 |website=Hindustan Times |language=en |access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Twitter|VivianDivine|name=DIVINE}}\n* {{Instagram|vivianakadivine|name=DIVINE}}\n[[Category:Indian rappers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n", "name_user": "157.43.192.210", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divine_(rapper)"}
{"title_page": "Changi Airport MRT station", "text_new": "{{short description|MRT station in Singapore}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox station\n| background = \n| name = {{SMRT Infobox Colour\n  | enname = Changi Airport\n  | zhname = \u6a1f\u5b9c\u673a\u573a\n  | taname = \u0b9a\u0bbe\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf \u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0ba8\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd\n  | msname = Changi Airport \n  | line = EAST WEST\n  | line2 =\n  | line3 =\n  | code = {{SMRT code |CG|2}}\n  | terminicode = [[File:MRT Singapore Destination 3.png|25px]] \n}}\n| type = [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit (MRT)]] station\n| image = File:Changi Airport MRT Station (EWL - Changi Branch) - Platform A.jpg\n| image_caption = Changi Airport station platform level\n| address = 70 Airport Boulevard<br />Singapore 819661<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.streetdirectory.com/sg/changi-airport/70-airport-boulevard-819661/5903_135223.html|title=Changi Airport (MRT Station) - 70 Airport Boulevard (S)819661|website=www.streetdirectory.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n| coordinates = {{Coord|1|21|26.54|N|103|59|19.81|E|type:railwaystation_region:SG|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| line = {{rail color box|system=SMRT|line=East West}}\n| other = [[Changi Airport Bus Terminal]], Taxi\n| structure = Underground\n| platform = 2 ([[1 island platform]])\n| depth = \n| levels = 1\n| tracks = 2\n| parking = Yes ([[Changi Airport]], [[Jewel Changi Airport]])\n| bicycle = Yes ([[Changi Airport]])\n| passengers = \n| pass_year = \n| pass_percent = \n| pass_system = \n| opened = {{start date and age|df=yes|2002|02|08}}\n| opening = {{start date and age|df=yes|2040}} ([[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]])\n| closed = \n| rebuilt = \n| electrified = Yes\n| ADA = Yes\n| code = {{SMRT code |CG|2}}\n| owned = \n| operator = [[File:SMRT Trains Logo.png|42px]] [[SMRT Trains|SMRT Trains Ltd]] ([[SMRT Corporation]]) (East West and Thomson\u2013East Coast lines)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/content/ltagov/en/getting_around/public_transport/rail_network.html|title=LTA {{!}} Getting Around {{!}} Public Transport {{!}} Rail Network|website=www.lta.gov.sg|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=SMRT Journeys | website=SMRT Journeys | url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/changi-airport/map/ | ref={{sfnref | SMRT Journeys}} | access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n| zone = \n| former = \n| services = {{S-rail|title=SMRT}}{{S-line|system=SMRT|line=East West|branch=Changi|previous=Expo|''Terminus''}}\n| mpassengers = \n| map_locator = {{Superimpose| base = MRT map EW.svg\n | base_width = 300px\n | base_caption = East West line\n | float = Red Dot.svg\n | float_width = 5px\n | float_caption = Changi Airport MRT station\n | x = 224\n | y = 69\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Changi Airport MRT station (CG2)''' is an underground [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit]] (MRT) station on the Changi Airport branch of the [[East West MRT line|East West line]] and is located in\u00a0[[Changi]],\u00a0[[Singapore]], within\u00a0[[Singapore Changi Airport]]. The station is built in an east-west direction with the two ends of the station connecting directly to Changi Airport Terminals 2 and 3. It is the eastern terminus of the branch and is currently the easternmost MRT station in Singapore, until the planned opening of\u00a0[[Aviation Park MRT station|Aviation Park station]]\u00a0in 2029.\n\nDuring the construction of [[Changi Airport Terminal 3|Terminal 3]] in 1994, proposals were made to build a new rail link connecting to and around the airport. The current two-station branch line was finalised in 1996 and construction began in 1999. The station opened on 8 February 2002, with passenger demand lower than expected. Nevertheless, it continues to provide an alternative transport option to the airport. On 25 May 2019, it was announced that the station will be incorporated as part of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]] (TEL), connecting to [[Infrastructure_of_Singapore_Changi_Airport#Terminal_5|Terminal 5]] by 2040.<ref name=\"LTMP 2040\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/new-mrt-stations-tel-extension-and-possible-new-rail-line-lta-2040-blueprint|title=New MRT stations, line extensions and a possible new rail line: LTA's 2040 blueprint|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref name=\"LTA Masterplan 2040\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=de83f659-4b0d-4609-840e-3deb3ac9b4b9|title=Land Transport Master Plan 2040: Bringing Singapore Together {{!}} Press Room {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Changi MRT.JPG|left|thumb|Changi Airport MRT station, featuring flight information box in addition to train route information]]\n[[File:CG1 changi airport faregates.jpg|left|thumb|Changi Airport is one of the few stations where faregates are on the same level as the platforms.]]\nBefore the MRT line, Changi Airport had been operating with no [[Airport rail link|rail link]] and with full reliance on [[Taxicabs of Singapore|taxi]] and [[Bus transport in Singapore|bus connections]] since the airport began operations in 1981. This was effective given the short {{convert|20|km|miles}} distance to the city via the [[East Coast Parkway]] and affordability of taxis and buses. Public buses instead linked commuters to nearby MRT stations at [[Bedok MRT station|Bedok]], [[Tampines MRT station|Tampines]] and [[Pasir Ris MRT station|Pasir Ris]]. Therefore, there were previously unsuccessful attempts to propose an extension to Changi Airport.<ref>{{Cite news|title=MRT Link to Airport: Not in next 10 years|date=17 May 1991|work=The Straits Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=No MRT Line to Changi yet|date=20 March 1992|work=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nThe idea of extending the Mass Rapid Transit system to Changi Airport was reconsidered when Terminal 3 was being built.<ref>{{Cite news|title=MRT extension to airport reconsidered.|date=2 August 1994|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> The earlier plans had long been made for a new line branching off from the existing East West line at Tanah Merah,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Next Stop: Changi Airport?|date=2 August 1994|work=The New Paper}}</ref> with some conceptual plans showing a tentative route alignment up to the airport along Airport Boulevard, continuing beyond the airport to Changi Point, before turning southwest back towards the city along the east coast of the island. The plans were finally announced by then [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore|Deputy Prime Minister]] [[Lee Hsien Loong]] on 15 November 1996.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore Mass Rapid Transit Employees' Union (SMRTEU)'s annual Dinner and Dance  |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1996111503/lhl19961115s.pdf |website=NAS |accessdate=10 July 2019 |date=15 November 1996}}</ref> However, the route alignment showed a deviation from previous plans. The final plan involved building only the first two stations, namely [[Expo MRT station|Expo]], and the Changi Airport station, the underground station built between Terminal 2 and Terminal 3. The alignment of the station at the airport has been switched perpendicularly to an east\u2013west direction, such that the station leads to two of the terminals directly from either end of the station.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19961212-1.2.51.7 |title=MRT Line will not go beyond passenger terminals |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 October 2019 |date=12 December 1996}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=changi+airport+mrt&KA=changi+airport+mrt&DF=02%2F01%2F1990&DT=01%2F09%2F2010&Display=0&NPT=&L=English&CTA=Article|title=Changi Airport MRT line details|date=12 December 1996|work=The Business Times|access-date=}}</ref> As part of the President's Challenge 2001, a part of a charity walk goes through the tunnel between Expo and Changi Airport stations.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seng Kim|first=Lim|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Chairty walk to talk place underground|date=12 August 2001|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Perfectly legal, and for a good cause!|date=9 September 2001|work=The New Paper|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Tan|first=Terence|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Tunnel walk a hit|date=9 September 2001|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\nThe Contract 504 for the construction of Changi Airport MRT station and its associated tunnels was awarded to Kumagai-Sembawang Joint Venture in October 1998. This project was a joint effort which combines Japanese technology and experience with local knowledge of subcontractor availability, supplier availability, due to the challenges of the construction of the station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://library.jsce.or.jp/jsce/open/00035/2001/56-cs/56-cs-0266.pdf|title=Underpinning Works in Construction of MRT Changi Airport Station in Singapore|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A groundbreaking ceremony was held on 29 January 1999. In the speech by then-communications minister [[Mah Bow Tan]] at the ceremony, he highlighted the challenges of the construction of the station, which would require close cooperation between various parties such as the [[Land Transport Authority]] (LTA), the [[Civil Aviation Authority of Singapore]] (CAAS) and the contractors. For the construction of Changi Airport station, different methods of deep excavations using various ground support systems were adopted. The construction work involved the challenge of deep excavation works right next to nearby developments such as the existing Terminal 2 structures.<ref name=\"Excavations\">{{Cite book|last=Murugamoorthy|first=C.|title=Behaviour of Various Support Systems for Deep Excavations, Changi Airport Underground MRT Station|publisher=Land Transport Authority|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In addition, close monitoring was needed for the construction of the {{convert|1|km|mi|adj=mid|-long}} tunnel leading to the station, which passes directly underneath the runway and airport terminal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1999012901.htm|title=Speech By Mr Mah Bow Tan, At The Changi Airport Line Ground Breaking Ceremony, 29 Jan 99, 10 am, Singapore Changi Airport|website=www.nas.gov.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> During the construction, [[CPG Corporation|CPG Consultants]], which was designing Terminal 3 at the time, provided 20 staff to complement the LTA team on the Changi Airport line extension.<ref name=\"CPG consultants\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpgcorp.com.sg/cpgc/Project/Project_Details?ProjectID=1312|title=CPG Consultants - Changi Airport Mass Rapid Transit Station (MRT)|website=www.cpgcorp.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n===Opening===\nThe station opened on 8 February 2002,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Completion%20Of%20The%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Extension/|title=Completion Of The Changi Airport MRT Extension|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Airport MRT stop to open tomorrow|date=7 February 2002|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> with the official opening ceremony of the Changi Airport MRT extension conducted on 27 February 2002.<ref name=\"Speech 1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech%20By%20Mr%20Yeo%20Cheow%20Tong%20At%20The%20Opening%20Of%20The%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Extension%20on%2027%20February%202002/|title=Speech By Mr Yeo Cheow Tong At The Opening Of The Changi Airport MRT Extension on 27 February 2002|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Since the station's opening, passenger traffic has been moderate, as most bus routes were maintained and continue to be a popular means of cheap, direct transport for local airport/airline employees, as well as travellers not living along the East West line. Many air travellers also prefer to continue taking taxis or private transport as not all of the MRT services have luggage racks in the trains.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seng Kim|first=Chew|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Taxi still the way to go for Changi air travellers|date=26 August 2002|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> However, taxi drivers claimed that the station has put them at a disadvantage, reporting a loss of 20 percent in earnings, with about 20,500 commuters using the station daily as of March 2002.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Phei Phei|first=Leong|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20020311-2.2.4.11?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article&QT=changi,airport,station&oref=article|title=Airport woes for cabbies|date=11 March 2002|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe initial numbering of the station was EW29, but was changed on 20 June 2003 to CG2.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=What SMRT said earlier|date=8 August 2001|work=The New Paper|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Incorporation into the TEL===\nOn 25 May 2019, the LTA announced an extension of the Thomson\u2013East Coast line (TEL) to Changi Airport. Set to be completed by 2040, The TEL will be extended from [[Sungei Bedok MRT station|Sungei Bedok station]] to serve the future Changi Airport Terminal 5, and the stretch between Tanah Merah and Changi Airport, which is currently part of the East-West line, will be transferred over to the TEL.<ref name=\"LTA Masterplan 2040\"/>\n\n===Incidents===\n*On 24 July 2002, a glass panel of the atria wall shattered. The area was quickly closed off, but train services were not affected.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/News-Centre/News/2002/Joint-Press-Release-By-Land-Transport-Authority-And-Singapore-MRT-Ltd-Atria-Wall-In-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/ |title=Joint Press Release By Land Transport Authority And Singapore MRT Ltd Atria Wall In Changi Airport MRT Station |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=24 July 2002 |publisher=[[Ministry of Transport (Singapore)|Ministry of Transport]] |access-date=16 January 2018 |quote=At 12.05pm, a piece of tempered glass at the atria wall in the Changi Airport MRT Station shattered into small fragments. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116135244/https://www.mot.gov.sg/News-Centre/News/2002/Joint-Press-Release-By-Land-Transport-Authority-And-Singapore-MRT-Ltd-Atria-Wall-In-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/ |archive-date=16 January 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Joint%20Press%20Release%20By%20Land%20Transport%20Authority%20And%20Singapore%20MRT%20Ltd%20Atria%20Wall%20In%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Station/|title=Joint Press Release By Land Transport Authority And Singapore MRT Ltd Atria Wall In Changi Airport MRT Station|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\n*On 24 September that year, a man died at the station, apparently having fallen five stories from the departure hall.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20030925-2.2.11.1|title=Man Dies at Changi Airport|date=25 September 2003|work=TODAY}}</ref>\n\n*On 17 January 2020, the rail operator SMRT said that it had found a crack in the crossing at Changi Airport MRT Station, found during inspection works in the morning. Trains have to be diverted to only one platform and have to travel at a slower speed as they approach the affected crossing.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/slower-train-service-changi-airport-mrt-station-until-jan-21-after-crack-spotted-track|title=Slower train service to Changi Airport MRT Station until Jan 21, after crack spotted on track|date=17 January 2020|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Station details and design==\n===Services===\n{{Routemap |title=Track layout |title-bg=#{{MRT color|East west}} |legend =track |map= utSTR!~MFADEg\\utSTR!~MFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to {{mrts|Expo}}\nutSTRg\\utSTRf \nutdSTRc2!~uvABZg2-\\d!~uv-ABZg3\\utdSTRc3 \nutdABZg+1\\utdSTRc14!~d-BS\\utdABZg+4 \nutSTR+BSl\\utSTR+BSr \nutSTR+BSl\\utSTR+BSr \nutSTR+BSl\\utSTR+BSr \nutdSTR\\dBS-\\utdSTR \nutENDEe\\utENDEe }}\nChangi Airport station is currently served by the Changi Airport Branch of the East West line, which connects to the airport from Tanah Merah station as a shuttle service. After the station was first opened on 8 February 2002, there were through services from [[Boon Lay MRT station|Boon Lay station]] to this station.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Boon Lay to Expo: MRT now running|date=20 December 2001|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> However, due to low ridership, the route reverted to being operated as a shuttle service from 22 July that year, with trains from Changi Airport station terminating at Tanah Merah station instead.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Board MRT to airport from Tanah Merah.|date=18 July 2003|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> \nThe first train from Changi Airport station departs at 5:31{{nbsp}}am on weekdays and Saturdays and 5:59{{nbsp}}am on Sundays instead, with the last train from the airport departing at 12:06{{nbsp}}am.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/changi-airport/first-and-last-train/|title=SMRT Journeys (First and last trains from Changi Airport)|website=journey.smrt.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> From Tanah Merah station, the first train towards the station departs at 5:20{{nbsp}}am on weekdays and Saturdays and 5:47{{nbsp}}am on Sundays instead, with the last train towards the airport from Tanah Merah station departing at 11:50{{nbsp}}pm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/tanah-merah/first-and-last-train/|title=SMRT Journeys (First and last trains from Tanah Merah)|website=journey.smrt.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\"Singapore Changi Airport\">{{cite web | title=Getting to the Airport | website=Singapore Changi Airport | url=https://www.changiairport.com/en/airport-guide/transport/getting-to-the-airport.html#anchorTrain | access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> [[Headway]]s between trains varies from 7 to 9 mins during peak hours, and 12 mins during off-peak hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://landtransportguru.net/changi-airport-station/|title=Changi Airport MRT Station {{!}} Land Transport Guru|date=2018-01-31|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\"TODAYonline 2014\">{{cite web | title=Tanah Merah station to get new tracks, platform | website=TODAYonline | date=26 August 2014 | url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/tanah-merah-station-get-new-tracks-platform | access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smrttrains.com.sg/Journey-with-Us/Travel-Information/Visiting-Singapore|title=Visting Singapore|website=www.smrttrains.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 2040, the station will be served by the TEL as part of the TEL line extension to the airport.<ref name=\"LTMP 2040\"/>\n===Design===\n[[File:Changi Airport MRT Station (EWL - Changi Branch) - Exit A.jpg|thumb|The panes of the glass atria walls seen from Exit A leading to the station|left]]\nVarious features have been incorporated into the design to make the station aesthetically pleasing to travellers.<ref name=\"Speech 1\"/> The station is designed by architectural firm [[Skidmore, Owings and Merrill]], featuring a large interior space and an illuminated {{convert|150|metre|ft}} linkbridge spanning over the island platform,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Goh|first=Sushma|title=RE:think - Designing For Wayfinding|publisher=Land Transport Authority|year=2018|isbn=|location=|pages=25}}</ref> connecting Terminals 2 and 3 with travellators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sgtrains.com/network-ewl.html#CG2|title=East-West Line|website=SGTrains|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> [[Australia|Australian]] engineering company Meinhardt Facades also provided structural design engineering of the glazing system and the tensioned cable structure of the two atria (approximately {{convert|60|metre|ft}} long by {{convert|20|metre|ft}} wide by {{convert|36|metre|ft}} high each) located at both ends of the station box adjacent to Terminal 2 and 3 of Changi Airport, with engineering input by [[Ove Arup and Partners]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.meinhardt.com.sg/projects/changi-airport-glass-atria/|title=Changi Airport Glass Atria {{!}} Meinhardt \u2013 Transforming Cities, Shaping the Future|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://andreamignini.com/03-MENU-METRO/images/singapore/Singapore%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Station%20Design%20&%20Construction%20of%20Glass%20Atria.pdf|title=Singapore Changi Airport MRT Station Design & Construction of Glass Atria|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Jewel Changi Airport]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Changi Airport MRT Station}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.smrt.com.sg/Trains/NetworkMap/ChangiAirport.aspx}}\n* [http://blog.smrt.com.sg/?p=159 Official blogsite]\n* [http://www.mynetbizz.com/MRT/To-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/HarbourFront-To-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station.cfm HarbourFront to Changi Airport MRT station route]\n* [http://landtransportguru.net/changi-airport-station/ Changi Airport MRT Station]\n\n{{Singapore MRT stations|east-west=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Changi Airport MRT station}}\n[[Category:Changi]]\n[[Category:Airport railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2002]]\n[[Category:Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore) stations]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Singapore]]\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 350268 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 61111 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 403 us -->\n\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 6083007 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 73546 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 925 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 338330 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 60129 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 416 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 410717 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 73630 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 861 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 321675 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 56806 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 409 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n", "text_old": "{{short description|MRT station in Singapore}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox station\n| background = \n| name = {{SMRT Infobox Colour\n  | enname = Changi Airport\n  | zhname = \u6a1f\u5b9c\u673a\u573a\n  | taname = \u0b9a\u0bbe\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf \u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0ba8\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd\n  | msname = Changi Airport \n  | line = EAST WEST\n  | line2 =\n  | line3 =\n  | code = {{SMRT code |CG|2}}\n  | terminicode = [[File:MRT Singapore Destination 3.png|25px]] \n}}\n| type = [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit (MRT)]] station\n| image = File:Changi Airport MRT Station (EWL - Changi Branch) - Platform A.jpg\n| image_caption = Changi Airport station platform level\n| address = 70 Airport Boulevard<br />Singapore 819661<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.streetdirectory.com/sg/changi-airport/70-airport-boulevard-819661/5903_135223.html|title=Changi Airport (MRT Station) - 70 Airport Boulevard (S)819661|website=www.streetdirectory.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n| coordinates = {{Coord|1|21|26.54|N|103|59|19.81|E|type:railwaystation_region:SG|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| line = {{rail color box|system=SMRT|line=East West}}\n| other = [[Changi Airport Bus Terminal]], Taxi\n| structure = Underground\n| platform = 2 ([[1 island platform]])\n| depth = \n| levels = 1\n| tracks = 2\n| parking = Yes ([[Changi Airport]], [[Jewel Changi Airport]])\n| bicycle = Yes ([[Changi Airport]])\n| passengers = \n| pass_year = \n| pass_percent = \n| pass_system = \n| opened = {{start date and age|df=yes|2002|02|08}}\n| opening = {{start date and age|df=yes|2040}} ([[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]])\n| closed = \n| rebuilt = \n| electrified = Yes\n| ADA = Yes\n| code = {{SMRT code |CG|2}}\n| owned = \n| operator = [[File:SMRT Trains Logo.png|42px]] [[SMRT Trains|SMRT Trains Ltd]] ([[SMRT Corporation]]) (East West and Thomson\u2013East Coast lines)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/content/ltagov/en/getting_around/public_transport/rail_network.html|title=LTA {{!}} Getting Around {{!}} Public Transport {{!}} Rail Network|website=www.lta.gov.sg|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=SMRT Journeys | website=SMRT Journeys | url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/changi-airport/map/ | ref={{sfnref | SMRT Journeys}} | access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n| zone = \n| former = \n| services = {{S-rail|title=SMRT}}{{S-line|system=SMRT|line=East West|branch=Changi|previous=Expo|''Terminus''}}\n| mpassengers = \n| map_locator = {{Superimpose| base = MRT map EW.svg\n | base_width = 300px\n | base_caption = East West line\n | float = Red Dot.svg\n | float_width = 5px\n | float_caption = Changi Airport MRT station\n | x = 224\n | y = 69\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Changi Airport MRT station (CG2)''' is an underground [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit]] (MRT) station on the Changi Airport branch of the [[East West MRT line|East West line]] and is located in\u00a0[[Changi]],\u00a0[[Singapore]], within\u00a0[[Singapore Changi Airport]]. The station is built in an east-west direction with the two ends of the station connecting directly to Changi Airport Terminals 2 and 3. It is the eastern terminus of the branch and is currently the easternmost MRT station in Singapore, until the planned opening of\u00a0[[Aviation Park MRT station|Aviation Park station]]\u00a0in 2029.\n\nDuring the construction of [[Changi Airport Terminal 3|Terminal 3]] in 1994, proposals were made to build a new rail link connecting to and around the airport. The current two-station branch line was finalised in 1996 and construction began in 1999. The station opened on 8 February 2002, with passenger demand lower than expected. Nevertheless, it continues to provide an alternative transport option to the airport. On 25 May 2019, it was announced that the station will be incorporated as part of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]] (TEL), connecting to [[Infrastructure_of_Singapore_Changi_Airport#Terminal_5|Terminal 5]] by 2040.<ref name=\"LTMP 2040\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/new-mrt-stations-tel-extension-and-possible-new-rail-line-lta-2040-blueprint|title=New MRT stations, line extensions and a possible new rail line: LTA's 2040 blueprint|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref name=\"LTA Masterplan 2040\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=de83f659-4b0d-4609-840e-3deb3ac9b4b9|title=Land Transport Master Plan 2040: Bringing Singapore Together {{!}} Press Room {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Changi MRT.JPG|left|thumb|Changi Airport MRT station, featuring flight information box in addition to train route information]]\n[[File:CG1 changi airport faregates.jpg|left|thumb|Changi Airport is one of the few stations where faregates are on the same level as the platforms.]]\nBefore the MRT line, Changi Airport had been operating with no [[Airport rail link|rail link]] and with full reliance on [[Taxicabs of Singapore|taxi]] and [[Bus transport in Singapore|bus connections]] since the airport began operations in 1981. This was effective given the short {{convert|20|km|miles}} distance to the city via the [[East Coast Parkway]] and affordability of taxis and buses. Public buses instead linked commuters to nearby MRT stations at [[Bedok MRT station|Bedok]], [[Tampines MRT station|Tampines]] and [[Pasir Ris MRT station|Pasir Ris]]. Therefore, there were previously unsuccessful attempts to propose an extension to Changi Airport.<ref>{{Cite news|title=MRT Link to Airport: Not in next 10 years|date=17 May 1991|work=The Straits Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=No MRT Line to Changi yet|date=20 March 1992|work=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nThe idea of extending the Mass Rapid Transit system to Changi Airport was reconsidered when Terminal 3 was being built.<ref>{{Cite news|title=MRT extension to airport reconsidered.|date=2 August 1994|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> The earlier plans had long been made for a new line branching off from the existing East West line at Tanah Merah,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Next Stop: Changi Airport?|date=2 August 1994|work=The New Paper}}</ref> with some conceptual plans showing a tentative route alignment up to the airport along Airport Boulevard, continuing beyond the airport to Changi Point, before turning southwest back towards the city along the east coast of the island. The plans were finally announced by then [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore|Deputy Prime Minister]] [[Lee Hsien Loong]] on 15 November 1996.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore Mass Rapid Transit Employees' Union (SMRTEU)'s annual Dinner and Dance  |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1996111503/lhl19961115s.pdf |website=NAS |accessdate=10 July 2019 |date=15 November 1996}}</ref> However, the route alignment showed a deviation from previous plans. The final plan involved building only the first two stations, namely [[Expo MRT station|Expo]], and the Changi Airport station, the underground station built between Terminal 2 and Terminal 3. The alignment of the station at the airport has been switched perpendicularly to an east\u2013west direction, such that the station leads to two of the terminals directly from either end of the station.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19961212-1.2.51.7 |title=MRT Line will not go beyond passenger terminals |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 October 2019 |date=12 December 1996}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=changi+airport+mrt&KA=changi+airport+mrt&DF=02%2F01%2F1990&DT=01%2F09%2F2010&Display=0&NPT=&L=English&CTA=Article|title=Changi Airport MRT line details|date=12 December 1996|work=The Business Times|access-date=}}</ref> As part of the President's Challenge 2001, a part of a charity walk goes through the tunnel between Expo and Changi Airport stations.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seng Kim|first=Lim|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Chairty walk to talk place underground|date=12 August 2001|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Perfectly legal, and for a good cause!|date=9 September 2001|work=The New Paper|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Tan|first=Terence|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Tunnel walk a hit|date=9 September 2001|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\nThe Contract 504 for the construction of Changi Airport MRT station and its associated tunnels was awarded to Kumagai-Sembawang Joint Venture in October 1998. This project was a joint effort which combines Japanese technology and experience with local knowledge of subcontractor availability, supplier availability, due to the challenges of the construction of the station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://library.jsce.or.jp/jsce/open/00035/2001/56-cs/56-cs-0266.pdf|title=Underpinning Works in Construction of MRT Changi Airport Station in Singapore|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A groundbreaking ceremony was held on 29 January 1999. In the speech by then-communications minister [[Mah Bow Tan]] at the ceremony, he highlighted the challenges of the construction of the station, which would require close cooperation between various parties such as the [[Land Transport Authority]] (LTA), the [[Civil Aviation Authority of Singapore]] (CAAS) and the contractors. For the construction of Changi Airport station, different methods of deep excavations using various ground support systems were adopted. The construction work involved the challenge of deep excavation works right next to nearby developments such as the existing Terminal 2 structures.<ref name=\"Excavations\">{{Cite book|last=Murugamoorthy|first=C.|title=Behaviour of Various Support Systems for Deep Excavations, Changi Airport Underground MRT Station|publisher=Land Transport Authority|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In addition, close monitoring was needed for the construction of the {{convert|1|km|mi|adj=mid|-long}} tunnel leading to the station, which passes directly underneath the runway and airport terminal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1999012901.htm|title=Speech By Mr Mah Bow Tan, At The Changi Airport Line Ground Breaking Ceremony, 29 Jan 99, 10 am, Singapore Changi Airport|website=www.nas.gov.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> During the construction, [[CPG Corporation|CPG Consultants]], which was designing Terminal 3 at the time, provided 20 staff to complement the LTA team on the Changi Airport line extension.<ref name=\"CPG consultants\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpgcorp.com.sg/cpgc/Project/Project_Details?ProjectID=1312|title=CPG Consultants - Changi Airport Mass Rapid Transit Station (MRT)|website=www.cpgcorp.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n===Opening===\nThe station opened on 8 February 2002,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Completion%20Of%20The%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Extension/|title=Completion Of The Changi Airport MRT Extension|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Airport MRT stop to open tomorrow|date=7 February 2002|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> with the official opening ceremony of the Changi Airport MRT extension conducted on 27 February 2002.<ref name=\"Speech 1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech%20By%20Mr%20Yeo%20Cheow%20Tong%20At%20The%20Opening%20Of%20The%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Extension%20on%2027%20February%202002/|title=Speech By Mr Yeo Cheow Tong At The Opening Of The Changi Airport MRT Extension on 27 February 2002|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Since the station's opening, passenger traffic has been moderate, as most bus routes were maintained and continue to be a popular means of cheap, direct transport for local airport/airline employees, as well as travellers not living along the East West line. Many air travellers also prefer to continue taking taxis or private transport as not all of the MRT services have luggage racks in the trains.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seng Kim|first=Chew|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Taxi still the way to go for Changi air travellers|date=26 August 2002|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> However, taxi drivers claimed that the station has put them at a disadvantage, reporting a loss of 20 percent in earnings, with about 20,500 commuters using the station daily as of March 2002.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Phei Phei|first=Leong|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20020311-2.2.4.11?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article&QT=changi,airport,station&oref=article|title=Airport woes for cabbies|date=11 March 2002|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe initial numbering of the station was EW29, but was changed on 20 June 2003 to CG2.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=What SMRT said earlier|date=8 August 2001|work=The New Paper|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Incorporation into the TEL===\nOn 25 May 2019, the LTA announced an extension of the Thomson\u2013East Coast line (TEL) to Changi Airport. Set to be completed by 2040, The TEL will be extended from [[Sungei Bedok MRT station|Sungei Bedok station]] to serve the future Changi Airport Terminal 5, and the stretch between Tanah Merah and Changi Airport, which is currently part of the East-West line, will be transferred over to the TEL.<ref name=\"LTA Masterplan 2040\"/>\n\n===Incidents===\n*On 24 July 2002, a glass panel of the atria wall shattered. The area was quickly closed off, but train services were not affected.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/News-Centre/News/2002/Joint-Press-Release-By-Land-Transport-Authority-And-Singapore-MRT-Ltd-Atria-Wall-In-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/ |title=Joint Press Release By Land Transport Authority And Singapore MRT Ltd Atria Wall In Changi Airport MRT Station |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=24 July 2002 |publisher=[[Ministry of Transport (Singapore)|Ministry of Transport]] |access-date=16 January 2018 |quote=At 12.05pm, a piece of tempered glass at the atria wall in the Changi Airport MRT Station shattered into small fragments. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116135244/https://www.mot.gov.sg/News-Centre/News/2002/Joint-Press-Release-By-Land-Transport-Authority-And-Singapore-MRT-Ltd-Atria-Wall-In-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/ |archive-date=16 January 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Joint%20Press%20Release%20By%20Land%20Transport%20Authority%20And%20Singapore%20MRT%20Ltd%20Atria%20Wall%20In%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Station/|title=Joint Press Release By Land Transport Authority And Singapore MRT Ltd Atria Wall In Changi Airport MRT Station|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\n*On 24 September that year, a man died at the station, apparently having fallen five stories from the departure hall.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20030925-2.2.11.1|title=Man Dies at Changi Airport|date=25 September 2003|work=TODAY}}</ref>\n\n*On 17 January 2020, the rail operator SMRT said that it had found a crack in the crossing at Changi Airport MRT Station, found during inspection works in the morning. Trains have to be diverted to only one platform and have to travel at a slower speed as they approach the affected crossing.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/slower-train-service-changi-airport-mrt-station-until-jan-21-after-crack-spotted-track|title=Slower train service to Changi Airport MRT Station until Jan 21, after crack spotted on track|date=17 January 2020|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Station details and design==\n===Services===\n{{Routemap |title=Track layout |title-bg=#{{MRT color|East west}} |legend =track |map= utSTR!~MFADEg\\utSTR!~MFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to {{mrts|Expo}}\nutSTRg\\utSTRf \nutdSTRc2!~uvABZg2-\\d!~uv-ABZg3\\utdSTRc3 \nutdABZg+1\\utdSTRc14!~d-BS\\utdABZg+4 \nutSTR+BSl\\utSTR+BSr \nutSTR+BSl\\utSTR+BSr \nutSTR+BSl\\utSTR+BSr \nutdSTR\\dBS-\\utdSTR \nutENDEe\\utENDEe }}\nChangi Airport station is currently served by the Changi Airport Branch of the East West line, which connects to the airport from Tanah Merah station as a shuttle service. After the station was first opened on 8 Feburary 2002, there were through services from [[Boon Lay MRT station|Boon Lay station]] to this station.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Boon Lay to Expo: MRT now running|date=20 December 2001|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> However, due to low ridership, the route reverted to being operated as a shuttle service from 22 July that year, with trains from Changi Airport station terminating at Tanah Merah station instead.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Board MRT to airport from Tanah Merah.|date=18 July 2003|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> \nThe first train from Changi Airport station departs at 5:31{{nbsp}}am on weekdays and Saturdays and 5:59{{nbsp}}am on Sundays instead, with the last train from the airport departing at 12:06{{nbsp}}am.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/changi-airport/first-and-last-train/|title=SMRT Journeys (First and last trains from Changi Airport)|website=journey.smrt.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> From Tanah Merah station, the first train towards the station departs at 5:20{{nbsp}}am on weekdays and Saturdays and 5:47{{nbsp}}am on Sundays instead, with the last train towards the airport from Tanah Merah station departing at 11:50{{nbsp}}pm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/tanah-merah/first-and-last-train/|title=SMRT Journeys (First and last trains from Tanah Merah)|website=journey.smrt.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\"Singapore Changi Airport\">{{cite web | title=Getting to the Airport | website=Singapore Changi Airport | url=https://www.changiairport.com/en/airport-guide/transport/getting-to-the-airport.html#anchorTrain | access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> [[Headway]]s between trains varies from 7 to 9 mins during peak hours, and 12 mins during off-peak hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://landtransportguru.net/changi-airport-station/|title=Changi Airport MRT Station {{!}} Land Transport Guru|date=2018-01-31|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\"TODAYonline 2014\">{{cite web | title=Tanah Merah station to get new tracks, platform | website=TODAYonline | date=26 August 2014 | url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/tanah-merah-station-get-new-tracks-platform | access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smrttrains.com.sg/Journey-with-Us/Travel-Information/Visiting-Singapore|title=Visting Singapore|website=www.smrttrains.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 2040, the station will be served by the TEL as part of the TEL line extension to the airport.<ref name=\"LTMP 2040\"/>\n===Design===\n[[File:Changi Airport MRT Station (EWL - Changi Branch) - Exit A.jpg|thumb|The panes of the glass atria walls seen from Exit A leading to the station|left]]\nVarious features have been incorporated into the design to make the station aesthetically pleasing to travellers.<ref name=\"Speech 1\"/> The station is designed by architectural firm [[Skidmore, Owings and Merrill]], featuring a large interior space and an illuminated {{convert|150|metre|ft}} linkbridge spanning over the island platform,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Goh|first=Sushma|title=RE:think - Designing For Wayfinding|publisher=Land Transport Authority|year=2018|isbn=|location=|pages=25}}</ref> connecting Terminals 2 and 3 with travellators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sgtrains.com/network-ewl.html#CG2|title=East-West Line|website=SGTrains|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> [[Australia|Australian]] engineering company Meinhardt Facades also provided structural design engineering of the glazing system and the tensioned cable structure of the two atria (approximately {{convert|60|metre|ft}} long by {{convert|20|metre|ft}} wide by {{convert|36|metre|ft}} high each) located at both ends of the station box adjacent to Terminal 2 and 3 of Changi Airport, with engineering input by [[Ove Arup and Partners]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.meinhardt.com.sg/projects/changi-airport-glass-atria/|title=Changi Airport Glass Atria {{!}} Meinhardt \u2013 Transforming Cities, Shaping the Future|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://andreamignini.com/03-MENU-METRO/images/singapore/Singapore%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Station%20Design%20&%20Construction%20of%20Glass%20Atria.pdf|title=Singapore Changi Airport MRT Station Design & Construction of Glass Atria|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Jewel Changi Airport]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Changi Airport MRT Station}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.smrt.com.sg/Trains/NetworkMap/ChangiAirport.aspx}}\n* [http://blog.smrt.com.sg/?p=159 Official blogsite]\n* [http://www.mynetbizz.com/MRT/To-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/HarbourFront-To-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station.cfm HarbourFront to Changi Airport MRT station route]\n* [http://landtransportguru.net/changi-airport-station/ Changi Airport MRT Station]\n\n{{Singapore MRT stations|east-west=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Changi Airport MRT station}}\n[[Category:Changi]]\n[[Category:Airport railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2002]]\n[[Category:Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore) stations]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Singapore]]\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 350268 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 61111 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 403 us -->\n\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 6083007 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 7354