13 Women's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay}}\n|{{flag|Great Britain and N.I.}}<br>[[Shana Cox]]<br>[[Nicola Sanders]]<br>[[Christine Ohuruogu]]<br>[[Perri Shakes-Drayton]]\n|{{flag|United States}}<br>[[Leslie Cole (athlete)|Leslie Cole]]<br>[[Natasha Hastings]]<br>[[Jernail Hayes]]<br>[[Sanya Richards-Ross]]\n|{{flag|Russia}}<br>[[Yuliya Gushchina]]<br>[[Kseniya Aksyonova|Kseniya Ustalova]]<br>[[Marina Karnaushchenko]]<br>[[Aleksandra Fedoriva]]\n|-\n|[[2014 IAAF World Indoor Championships|2014 Sopot]]<br>{{DetailsLink|2014 IAAF World Indoor Championships \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay}}\n|{{flag|United States}}<br>[[Natasha Hastings]]<br>[[Joanna Atkins]]<br>[[Francena McCorory]]<br>[[Cassandra Tate]]<br>[[Jernail Hayes]]*<br>[[Monica Hargrove]]*\n|{{flag|Jamaica}}<br>[[Patricia Hall (athlete)|Patricia Hall]]<br>[[Anneisha McLaughlin-Whilby|Anneisha McLaughlin]]<br>[[Kaliese Spencer]]<br>[[Stephenie Ann McPherson]]<br>[[Verone Chambers]]*<br>[[Natoya Goule]]*\n|{{flag|Great Britain and N.I.}}<br>[[Eilidh Doyle|Eilidh Child]]<br>[[Shana Cox]]<br>[[Margaret Adeoye]]<br>[[Christine Ohuruogu]]<br>[[Victoria Ohuruogu]]*\n|-\n|[[2016 IAAF World Indoor Championships|2016 Portland]]<br>{{DetailsLink|2016 IAAF World Indoor Championships \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay}}\n|{{flag|United States}}<br>[[Natasha Hastings]]<br>[[Quanera Hayes]]<br>[[Courtney Okolo]]<br>[[Ashley Spencer (athlete)|Ashley Spencer]]\n|{{flag|Poland}}<br>[[Ewelina Ptak]]<br>[[Ma\u0142gorzata Ho\u0142ub]]<br>[[Magdalena Gorzkowska]]<br>[[Justyna \u015awi\u0119ty]]\n|{{flag|Romania}}<br>[[Adelina Pastor]]<br>[[Mirela Lavric]]<br>[[Andrea Mikl\u00f3s]]<br>[[Bianca R\u0103zor]]\n|}\n<small>'''Note''' * Indicates athletes who ran only in the preliminary round and also received medals.</small>\n\n==Notable splits==\n\n===Men===\n* [[Herb McKenley]] ([[Jamaica]]) ran a 44.6 split in the [[Athletics at the 1952 Summer Olympics|1952 Helsinki Olympic]] final.\n* [[Ron Freeman]] (USA) ran a 43.2 split in the [[Athletics at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968 Mexico Olympic]] final.\n* [[Julius Sang]] ([[Kenya]]) ran a 43.6 split in the [[Athletics at the 1972 Summer Olympics|1972 Munich Olympic]] final.\n* [[Alberto Juantorena]] (Cuba) ran a 43.7 split in the [[1977 IAAF World Cup]] event as part of the Americas team.\n* [[Quincy Watts]] ran a 43.1 split and [[Steve Lewis (sprinter)|Steve Lewis]] (USA) ran a 43.4 split in the [[Athletics at the 1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Barcelona Olympic]] final.\n* [[Butch Reynolds]] ran a 43.23 split and [[Michael Johnson (athlete)|Michael Johnson]] (both USA) ran a 42.91 split in the [[1993 World Championships in Athletics|1993 Stuttgart World Championship]] final; the USA team's final time of 2:54.29 is the current world record.\n* [[Mark Richardson (sprinter)|Mark Richardson]] (GBR) ran a 43.57 split and [[Davian Clarke]] (JAM) ran a 43.51 split in the [[1997 World Championships in Athletics|1997 Athens World Championship]] final.\n* [[Jeremy Wariner]] (USA) ran a 43.10 split in the [[2007 World Championships in Athletics|2007 Osaka World Championship]] final.\n* [[Jeremy Wariner]] (USA) ran a 43.18 split in the [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Beijing Olympic]] final.\n* [[Michael Norman (sprinter)|Michael Norman]] (USA) ran a 43.06 split in the 2018 NCAA West Preliminaries final.<ref>{{cite news|title=Norman and Benjamin the latest stars to shine in the IAAF Diamond League|url=https://www.iaaf.org/news/feature/michael-norman-rai-benjamin-diamond-league|accessdate=15 January 2019|newspaper=IAAF|date=1 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Women===\n* [[Jarmila Kratochv\u00edlov\u00e1]] ([[Czechoslovakia|CZE]]) ran a 47.6 split in the [[1982 European Athletics Championships|1982 Athens European Championship final]], a 47.75 split in the [[1983 World Championships in Athletics|1983 Helsinki World Championship final]], and a 47.9 split in the 1983 Europa Cup in London. \n* [[Marita Koch]] ([[East Germany|GDR]]) ran a 47.70 split in Erfurt 1984, a 47.9 split in the 1982 European Championship final, and a 47.9 split at the [[1985 IAAF World Cup|1985 Canberra World Cup]].\n* [[Allyson Felix]] (USA) ran a 47.72 split in the [[2015 World Championships in Athletics|2015 Beijing World Championships final]], a 48.01 split in the [[2007 World Championships in Athletics|2007 Osaka World Championships final]], and a 48.20 split in the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London Olympic final]].\n* [[Olga Nazarova]] and [[Olga Bryzgina]] ([[USSR]]) both ran a 47.80 split in the [[Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Seoul Olympic]] final; the Soviet team's final time of 3:15.17 is the current world record.\n* [[Florence Griffith-Joyner]] (USA) ran a 48.08 split in the 1988 Seoul Olympic final.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://iaaf.gekko.de/?a=relays&d=4x400-metres-relay IAAF list of 4x400-metres-relay records in XML]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Athletics events}}\n{{Portal bar|Athletics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:4 by 400 metres relay}}\n[[Category:Track relay races]]\n[[Category:Events in track and field]]\n[[Category:4 \u00d7 400 metres relay|*]]\n[[Category:Summer Olympic disciplines in athletics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox athletics event\n|event= 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay\n|image= 4 x 400 m men final Barcelona 2010.jpg\n|image_upright= 1.15\n|caption= 4 \u00d7 400 m men relay at the European Championships in Barcelona 2010 (Martyn Rooney (GBR), Thomas Schneider (GER), Kacper Koz\u0142owski (POL), Jonathan Borl\u00e9e (BEL), Vladimir Krasnov (RUS), Teddy Venel (FRA))\n|WRmen= {{USA}} <small>([[Andrew Valmon]], [[Quincy Watts]], [[Butch Reynolds]], [[Michael Johnson (sprinter)|Michael Johnson]])</small> 2:54.29 (1993)\n|ORmen= {{USA}} <small>([[LaShawn Merritt]], [[Angelo Taylor]], [[David Neville (sprinter)|David Neville]], [[Jeremy Wariner]])</small> 2:55.39 (2008)\n|WRwomen= {{URS}} <small>([[Tatyana Ledovskaya]], [[Olga Nazarova]], [[Mariya Pinigina]], [[Olga Bryzgina]])</small> 3:15.17 (1988)\n|ORwomen= {{URS}} <small>([[Tatyana Ledovskaya]], [[Olga Nazarova]], [[Mariya Pinigina]], [[Olga Bryzgina]])</small> 3:15.17 (1988)\n}}\n\nThe '''4&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;400&nbsp;metres relay''' or long relay is an athletics [[track and field|track event]] in which teams consist of four runners who each complete 400&nbsp;metres or one lap. It is traditionally the final event of a track meet. At top class events, the first 500&nbsp;metres is run in lanes. Start lines are thus staggered over a greater distance than in an individual [[400 metres|400&nbsp;metres]] race; the runners then typically move to the inside of the track. The slightly longer '''4 \u00d7 440 yards relay''' was a formerly run British and American event, until [[metrication]] was completed in the 1970s.\n\n[[Relay race]] runners typically carry a relay baton which they must transfer between teammates. Runners have a 20&nbsp;m box (usually marked with blue lines) in which to transfer the baton. The first transfer is made within the staggered lane lines; for the second and third transfers, runners typically line up across the track despite the fact that runners are usually running in line on the inside of the track. This prevents confusion and collisions during transfer. Unlike the [[4 \u00d7 100 metres relay|4&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;100&nbsp;m]] relay, runners in the 4&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;400 typically look back and grasp the baton from the incoming runner, due to the fatigue of the incoming runner, and the wider margins allowed by the longer distance of the race. Consequently, disqualification is rare.\n\nAs runners have a running start, split times cannot be compared to individual 400 m performances. Internationally, the U.S. men's team has dominated the event, but have been challenged by [[Jamaica]] in the 1950s and Britain in the 1990s.  The current men's Olympic champions are from the [[United States]].\n\nAccording to the IAAF rules, world records in relays can only be set if all team members have the same nationality.\n\n[[Mixed 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay|Mixed-gendered 4 \u00d7 400 metres relays]] were introduced at the [[2017 IAAF World Relays]], with the IAAF first recognizing a world record in that event at the [[2019 World Athletics Championships]].\n\n==Records==\n{{see also|Men's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay world record progression|Women's 4 \u00d7 400 metres relay world record progression}}\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!colspan=5|Men's Outdoor World Record<ref>{{cite web|title=4x400 Metres Relay Records \u2013 outdoor|url=http://www.iaaf.org/statistics/records/inout=o/discType=5/disc=4X4/detail.html|publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations]]|accessdate=1 September 2011}}</ref> \n|-\n!Country !!Members !!Venue !!Date !!Time\n|-\n|{{flagicon|USA}} United States ||[[Andrew Valmon]], [[Quincy Watts]], [[Butch Reynolds]], [[Michael Johnson (sprinter)|Michael Johnson]] ||[[Stuttgart]], Germany ||22 August 1993 ||2:54.29\n|}\n''Note:'' The IAAF rescinded a time of 2:54.20 set at Uniondale on 22 July 1998 by the United States ([[Jerome Young]], [[Antonio Pettigrew]], [[Tyree Washington]], [[Michael Johnson (athlete)|Michael Johnson]]) on 12 August 2008 after Pettigrew admitted to using human growth hormone and EPO between 1997 and 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=IAAF deletes Americans\u2019 4x400m world record from the books|url=http://thestar.com.my/sports/story.asp?file=/2008/8/13/olympics/22071007&sec=Olympics|accessdate=1 September 2011|newspaper=The Star Online|date=13 August 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019125624/http://thestar.com.my/sports/story.asp?file=%2F2008%2F8%2F13%2Folympics%2F22071007&sec=Olympics|archivedate=19 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!colspan=5|Men's Indoor World Record\n|-\n!Country !!Members !!Venue !!Date !!Time\n|-\n|{{flagicon|POL}} Poland || [[Karol Zalewski]], [[Rafa\u0142 Omelko]], [[\u0141ukasz Krawczuk]], [[Jakub Krzewina]] ||[[Birmingham]], [[United Kingdom]] ||4 March 2018 ||3:01.77\n|}\n\n''Note:'' A time of 3:00.77 by the [[University of California|USC]] team ([[Zach Shinnick]], [[Rai Benjamin]], [[Ricky Morgan Jr.]], [[Michael Norman (sprinter)|Michael Norman]]) at the 2018 NCAA Division I Championship was rejected as a record as Benjamin was a citizen of Antigua & Barbuda, and the others are US citizens. US runners [[Ilolo Izu]], [[Robert Grant (athlete)|Robert Grant]], [[Devin Dixon]] and [[Mylik Kerley]] recorded a 3:01.39 in the same race, which has not yet been ratified.<ref>{{cite news|title=Norman breaks world indoor 400m record at NCAA Indoor Championships|url=https://www.iaaf.org/news/report/ncaa-indoor-championships-2018-norman-400-wor|publisher=IAAF|author=Roy Jordan|date=10 March 2018|accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!colspan=5|Women's Outdoor World Record\n|-\n!Country !!Members !!Venue !!Date !!Time\n|-\n|{{flagicon|USSR}} USSR ||[[Tatyana Ledovskaya]] (BLR), [[Olga Nazarova]] (RUS), [[Mariya Pinigina]] (UKR), [[Olga Bryzgina]] (UKR) ||[[Seoul, Korea]] ||1 October 1988 ||3:15.17\n|}\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!colspan=5|Women's Indoor World Record \n|-\n!Country !!Members !!Venue !!Date !!Time\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Russia}} Russia ||[[Yuliya Gushchina]], [[Olga Kotlyarova]], [[Olga Zaytseva]], [[Olesya Krasnomovets]] ||Glasgow, Scotland ||27 January 2006 ||3:23.37\n|}\n\n==All-time top 10 by country==\n===Men===\n*Correct as of August 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=All-time men's best 4 \u00d7 400m Relay|url=https://www.iaaf.org/records/toplists/relays/4x400-metres-relay/outdoor/men/senior|publisher=IAAF|date=24 August 2019|accessdate=24 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=All-time men's best 4 \u00d7 400m Relay|url=http://www.alltime-athletics.com/m4x400ok.htm|publisher=alltime-athletics.com|date=13 August 2017|accessdate=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Rank\n!Time\n!Team\n!Nation\n!Date\n!Place\n!Ref